{"title_page": "Yasunori Nishiki", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Yasunori Nishiki\n| native_name = \u897f\u6728 \u5eb7\u667a\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| alias = Vivian\n| background = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|07|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], Japan\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Composer\n* arranger\n}}\n| genre = {{flatlist| \n* [[Orchestra]]l\n* [[progressive rock]]\n* [[symphonic rock]]\n* [[video game music]]\n}}\n| instruments = [[Electronic keyboard|Keyboards]]\n| website = {{URL|http://yasunorinishiki.com/}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Yasunori Nishiki'''|\u897f\u6728 \u5eb7\u667a|Nishiki Yasunori|born July 10, 1985}} is a Japanese [[composer]] and [[arranger]], best known for his work on the soundtracks for ''[[Octopath Traveler]]'' and various [[music video game]] series devloped by [[Bemani]]. He is currently a freelance composer, and has since produce soundtracks for both video games and [[anime]].\n\n==Biography==\nNishiki was born on July 10, 1985 in [[Kanagawa Prefecture]].<ref name=\"about\"/> He started taking piano lessons when he was a child, but became interested in music when he became a fan of the Japanese band Spitz. After which, he bought some sheet music for their songs and began to write his own compositions on the piano.<ref name=\"vgm\"/> After graduating from [[Tokyo College of Music]], he began to work as a music composer for [[Konami]],<ref name=\"gamerpros\"/> and worked on titles such as ''Quiz Magic Academy'' series, and arranged the [[national anthems]] for ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer 2011]]'', which are also used in the [[Pro Evolution Soccer|further installments]] in the series.<ref name=\"pes\">{{cite web|url=http://yasunorinishiki.com/portfolio/pes/|script-title=ja:\u30a6\u30a4\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u30a4\u30ec\u30d6\u30f3 / Pro Evolution Soccer (2011-)|website=yasunorinishiki.com|accessdate=April 21, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref> He had also produced several tracks for various [[music video game]] series such as ''[[Reflec Beat]]'', ''[[Pop'n Music]]'', and ''[[Jubeat]]'' under the alias Vivian.<ref name=\"bemani\">{{cite web|url=http://yasunorinishiki.com/portfolio/bemani/|script-title=ja:BEMANI\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba|website=yasunorinishiki.com|accessdate=April 21, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nHe left Konami to pursue his career as a freelancer, and began to expand his works for various non-gaming projects such as [[anime]] and [[puppet shows]].<ref name=\"gamerpros\"/> His first major project was the soundtrack for the video game ''[[Octopath Traveler]]''; the soundtrack received positive reception from critics and fans,<ref>{{cite web|last=Craddock|first=Ryan|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/08/octopath_traveler_composer_feels_relieved_that_fans_enjoy_the_games_soundtrack|title=Octopath Traveler Composer Feels \"Relieved\" That Fans Enjoy The Game's Soundtrack|publisher=Nintendo Life|date=August 30, 2018|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> and has since spawn many arrangement albums and has also been performed live in concerts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Craddock|first=Ryan|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2019/04/octopath_traveler_is_getting_its_first_live_concert_this_july|title=Octopath Traveler Is Getting Its First Live Concert This July|publisher=Nintendo Life|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> He would later worked on the anime ''[[Granblue Fantasy The Animation]]'',<ref name=\"resume\"/> and ''[[Azur Lane]]''.<ref name=\"azur\"/>\n\nHe has collaborated with [[Kohei Tanaka (composer)|Kohei Tanaka]] as a synthesizer for many of his works, including ''[[Gravity Rush 2]]'' and ''[[One Piece (TV series)|One Piece]]''.<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n\n==Works==\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Note(s)\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2010\n| ''Quiz Magic Academy VII'' || with various others || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer 2011]]'' || arranged the [[national anthems]] || <ref name=\"pes\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n| ''Quiz Magic Academy VIII'' || with various others || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''Frontier Gate'' || with Naoyuki Sato, Masato Nakayama, and [[Junpei Fujita]] || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"6\" | 2012\n| ''[[NeverDead]]'' || with various others || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''Quiz Magic Academy: Kenja no Tobira'' || with various others || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Reflec Beat]] colette -Winter-'' || \"guerre \u00e0 outrance\" || <ref name=\"bemani\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Monster Retsuden Oreca Battle]]'' || with Nobuko Toda || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Pop'n Music]] Sunny Park'' || \"Haitoku to jaaku no epitaph\" || <ref name=\"bemani\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Jubeat]] Saucer'' || \"Vanity\" and \"le mirage\" || <ref name=\"bemani\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | 2013\n| ''[[Dragon Collection]]'' || also sound director || <ref name=\"bemani\"/>\n|-\n| ''Reflec Beat colette -Summer-'' || \"Legendary Dragon\" || <ref name=\"bemani\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Beatmania IIDX 21: Spada]]'' || \"Shattered control\" || <ref name=\"bemani\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2015\n| ''Otoca D'or'' || \"Sen no Komorebi\" || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Lord of Vermilion]] Arena'' || with various others || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"4\" | 2016\n| ''[[Show by Rock!!]]'' || \"My Precious Sign\" || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Quiz RPG: The World of Mystic Wiz]]'' || with various others || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Endride]]: X Fragments'' || with various others || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Fate/Extella: The Umbral Star]]'' || \"ex:tella\" || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n| ''[[Gravity Rush 2]]'' || synthesizer || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Terra Battle 2]]'' || arrangements with various others ||\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2018\n| ''[[Princess Connect! Re:Dive]]'' || with various others || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://ototoy.jp/_/default/p/316251|title=PRINCESS CONNECT! Re:Dive ORIGINAL SOUNDTRACK|publisher=Ototoy|accessdate=April 21, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Octopath Traveler]]'' || || <ref name=\"vgm\"/><ref name=\"gamerpros\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2019\n| ''Renshin no Astral'' || with various others || <ref>{{cite web|last=Kashiwagi|first=Mizuki|script-title=ja:\u843d\u3061\u7269\u30c7\u30c3\u30ad\u30d0\u30c8\u30eb\u300e\u932c\u795e\u306e\u30a2\u30b9\u30c8\u30e9\u30eb\u300f\u914d\u4fe1\u8a18\u5ff5\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u4f5c\u66f2\u5bb6\u7de8\u3002\u5149\u7530\u5eb7\u5178\u6c0f\u3001\u4e0b\u6751\u967d\u5b50\u6c0f\u3089\u8c6a\u83ef\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc6\u4eba\u304c\u96c6\u3046|url=https://automaton-media.com/articles/interviewsjp/20191226-109737/|website=automaton-media.com|date=December 26, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Rakugaki Kingdom'' || \"Spectrum Seeker\" || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://rakugaki-kingdom.com/sound/|title=SOUND|website=rakugaki-kingdom.com|accessdate=April 21, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2020\n| ''[[Granblue Fantasy Versus]]'' || with Tsutomu Narita, Hidenori Maezawa, Nao Tokisawa, and Azusa Chiba ||\n|-\n| ''[[Final Fantasy VII Remake]]'' || with various others || <ref>{{cite tweet|last=Nishiki|first=Yasunori|user=yasunorinishiki|date=April 10, 2020|title=I played a part of the music for \"FINAL FANTASY VII REMAKE.\" It was a truly precious time for me to work on the music that is definitely imprinted in my DNA. You, had snowboarded endlessly in Gold Saucer 23 years ago, are now writing the battle music for that game!|number=1248484925960908806|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other projects===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Note(s)\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" | 2014\n| ''Oreca Omaeca Genkai Battle!! / [[Akira Kushida]]'' || \"Kessen! Burning\" || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2015\n| ''El Mundo / Risa Minami'' || synthesizer for \"Moroha no Tsurugi\" || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| ''Music College Alumni Joint Volunteer Project: Work Collection 1'' || \"SeTsuNa\" || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://hukuro-no-mori.booth.pm/items/162529|script-title=ja:\u97f3\u5927\u51fa\u8eab\u8005\u6709\u5fd7\u5408\u540c\u4f01\u753b\u3000\u4f5c\u54c1\u96c6\uff11|website=hukuro-no-mori.booth.pm|accessdate=April 21, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2016\n| ''[[Endride]]'' || [[anime]]; synthesizer ||\n|-\n| ''Izayoi Bonboriuta / Tsurezurenaru Ayatsuri Mugenan'' || arranged \"Gensou yo Sake\" || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" | 2017\n| ''[[Granblue Fantasy The Animation]]'' || anime; with [[Nobuo Uematsu]] and Tsutomu Narita || <ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" | 2018\n| ''Canvas / Risa Minami'' || \"Yoake no Ane Mosu\" || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingrecords.co.jp/cs/g/gKICJ-813/|script-title=ja:Canvas \u5357 \u91cc\u6c99|publisher=[[King Records (Japan)|King Records]]|accessdate=April 21, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | 2019\n| ''[[Kingdom Hearts]] Orchestra -World of Tres- Album'' || arranged \"Overture to the Decisive Battle\" || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khinsider.com/forums/index.php?threads/kingdom-hearts-orchestra-world-of-tres-setlist-and-special-messages.219714/|title=Kingdom Hearts Orchestra -World of Tres- Setlist and Special Messages|website=khinsider.com|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703152736/https://www.khinsider.com/forums/index.php?threads/kingdom-hearts-orchestra-world-of-tres-setlist-and-special-messages.219714/|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Octopath Traveler]] Arrangements Break & Boost -Extend-'' || || <ref>{{cite web|url=https://store.jp.square-enix.com/item/SQEX_10717.html|title=OCTOPATH TRAVELER Arrangements 